[normal]Third party interventions[bold]… In recent years the House has frequently been assisted by the submissions of statutory bodies and non-governmenta
[normal]l organisations on questions of general public importance. Leave is given to such bodies to intervene and make submissions, usually in writing but sometimes orally from the bar, in the expectation that their fund of knowledge or particular point of view wi
[normal]ll enable them to provide the House with a more rounded picture than it would otherwise obtain. The House is grateful to such bodies for their help.
[normal]Recognising this, the Supreme 
[normal]Court
[normal] will not ordinarily make costs orders against 
[normal]third
[normal] parties
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Once a matter is in court, the more important the subject, the more difficult the issues, the more help we need to try and get the right answer. ... No particular formality is required and t
[normal]he invitation is a very open one, but not I think abused.
[normal]Commenting that ‘provided they stick to the rules, interventions are enormously helpful’, she noted specifically that ‘[o]
[normal]ne
[normal] thing that interveners can do, which the parties may find it more diffic
[normal]ult and more costly to do, is to draw our attention to international jurisprudence which may be relevant to the issue’.
